00:00:25.620 --> 00:00:28.270
DAVID THORBURN: Good
afternoon, people.

00:00:28.270 --> 00:00:33.170
We begin this afternoon our--
if I'm right about this,

00:00:33.170 --> 00:00:35.480
I think I am, as
the syllabus shows--

00:00:35.480 --> 00:00:37.277
that this is the last
American film we'll

00:00:37.277 --> 00:00:38.360
be looking at in the term.

00:00:38.360 --> 00:00:42.060
So we're sort of finishing
of the Central American

00:00:42.060 --> 00:00:45.060
phase of our course
with tonight's film,

00:00:45.060 --> 00:00:47.690
Robert Altman's
McCabe &amp; Mrs. Miller.

00:00:47.690 --> 00:00:51.840
And I want to use this
afternoon's lecture

00:00:51.840 --> 00:00:55.890
to contextualize that moment of
the early '70s-- the late '60s

00:00:55.890 --> 00:00:58.280
and early '70s-- in
American film history.

00:00:58.280 --> 00:01:00.470
And to try to draw out
some of the implications

00:01:00.470 --> 00:01:05.069
of the astonishing
transformation that overtook

00:01:05.069 --> 00:01:08.050
American film in this period.

00:01:08.050 --> 00:01:10.970
We've been talking about
this topic in different ways

00:01:10.970 --> 00:01:12.140
all semester.

00:01:12.140 --> 00:01:16.090
So by now I think the narrative
that I've been implicitly

00:01:16.090 --> 00:01:17.850
following in the
course should already

00:01:17.850 --> 00:01:20.550
be overt for all of you.

00:01:20.550 --> 00:01:22.220
The film we're going
to see tonight,

00:01:22.220 --> 00:01:27.160
Robert Altman's
McCabe &amp; Mrs. Miller,

00:01:27.160 --> 00:01:31.010
can be understood as are
particularly clear example

00:01:31.010 --> 00:01:36.880
of the kind of transformation
and even subversion that

00:01:36.880 --> 00:01:40.480
becomes a dominant note
of American movie making

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:41.900
in the 1970s.

00:01:41.900 --> 00:01:43.890
And part of the
lecture today will

00:01:43.890 --> 00:01:49.530
be devoted to
speculating about why

00:01:49.530 --> 00:01:52.750
that transformation, why those
forms of subversion, occurred.

00:01:52.750 --> 00:01:55.650
And of course, if you've been
paying attention in the course,

00:01:55.650 --> 00:01:57.179
you know the answer
already and it's

00:01:57.179 --> 00:01:59.220
the answer that's already
embedded in the lecture

00:01:59.220 --> 00:01:59.950
outline.

00:01:59.950 --> 00:02:04.170
A new form of what I've been
calling consensus narrative

00:02:04.170 --> 00:02:09.954
emerges really decisively by
the middle and end of the 1960s

00:02:09.954 --> 00:02:11.590
and into the 1970s.

00:02:11.590 --> 00:02:16.370
It's a period that takes time
but, essentially, television

00:02:16.370 --> 00:02:19.670
supplants the movies
as the central story

00:02:19.670 --> 00:02:21.220
system of the society.

00:02:21.220 --> 00:02:23.850
Not that movies become
trivial or unimportant,

00:02:23.850 --> 00:02:28.620
but they begin to occupy
a new niche in the media

00:02:28.620 --> 00:02:30.280
ecology of the country.

00:02:30.280 --> 00:02:35.570
And I'll return to this matter
briefly in a few moments.

00:02:35.570 --> 00:02:39.310
But let me begin by
clarifying something

00:02:39.310 --> 00:02:42.480
about the importance of the
presence in our syllabus

00:02:42.480 --> 00:02:45.690
of McCabe &amp; Mrs. Miller
and more generally,

00:02:45.690 --> 00:02:47.600
the prominence we've
given in our course

00:02:47.600 --> 00:02:50.280
to the genre of
the Western film.

00:02:50.280 --> 00:02:53.330
So I ask you to remember the
sorts of things we were saying

00:02:53.330 --> 00:02:56.850
about genre forms generally.

00:02:56.850 --> 00:02:58.910
About the aptness--
even one one might

00:02:58.910 --> 00:03:01.250
think of as the
economic necessity

00:03:01.250 --> 00:03:05.840
genre forms for a
system that is based

00:03:05.840 --> 00:03:08.190
on the principle
of mass production.

00:03:08.190 --> 00:03:09.880
And I also want
to suggest to you

00:03:09.880 --> 00:03:12.710
that the particular
forms of genre story,

00:03:12.710 --> 00:03:16.080
the particular
kind of story that

00:03:16.080 --> 00:03:18.650
is told in a particular society
and certainly the ones that

00:03:18.650 --> 00:03:20.870
are told in the generic
forms that are chosen

00:03:20.870 --> 00:03:25.250
by American society, are going
to very powerfully reflect

00:03:25.250 --> 00:03:27.000
aspects of the culture.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:29.710
And we made a special
emphasis on the importance

00:03:29.710 --> 00:03:33.580
in our previous classes of
two particular genres that

00:03:33.580 --> 00:03:38.890
emerge with great
decisiveness in the sound era.

00:03:38.890 --> 00:03:44.490
Both identified by some scholars
as America's most distinctive

00:03:44.490 --> 00:03:46.750
contribution to world cinema.

00:03:46.750 --> 00:03:49.410
One form was the
screwball comedy

00:03:49.410 --> 00:03:52.450
and the elaborations on
comedy that developed

00:03:52.450 --> 00:03:54.670
through the '30s and 1940s.

00:03:54.670 --> 00:03:57.570
And the second form, the
second distinctive American

00:03:57.570 --> 00:04:00.000
contribution to film--
has some scholars

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:01.280
have sais-- is the Western.

00:04:01.280 --> 00:04:03.750
And we've talked a bit about
the nature of the Western

00:04:03.750 --> 00:04:06.580
and how the Western
as a form is rooted

00:04:06.580 --> 00:04:08.790
in the assumptions
and preoccupations

00:04:08.790 --> 00:04:10.000
of American culture.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:15.180
How it grows out of an
historical actuality--

00:04:15.180 --> 00:04:18.940
the period roughly
from 1860 to 1890--

00:04:18.940 --> 00:04:25.510
when the Civil War occurred,
when the range wars occurred,

00:04:25.510 --> 00:04:29.790
when the when the great
gold discoveries were made

00:04:29.790 --> 00:04:32.850
at the California
Gold Rush, the laying

00:04:32.850 --> 00:04:34.450
of the transcontinental
railroad.

00:04:34.450 --> 00:04:36.480
All of these
historical realities

00:04:36.480 --> 00:04:40.740
that become mythic elements
in the founding story that

00:04:40.740 --> 00:04:44.380
becomes the epic account
of American identity.

00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:48.940
The epic account of
America's founding.

00:04:48.940 --> 00:04:52.340
And I've suggested that the
creation of that mythology,

00:04:52.340 --> 00:04:56.320
expressed so powerfully
and complexly often--

00:04:56.320 --> 00:04:59.520
and disturbingly too because
there's a racism, as we've

00:04:59.520 --> 00:05:02.610
said and imperialism
implicit in certain aspects

00:05:02.610 --> 00:05:09.710
of the Western mythology--
that fundamental energy

00:05:09.710 --> 00:05:13.110
of the genre, as
we've suggested,

00:05:13.110 --> 00:05:15.860
is not only deeply rooted
in American culture,

00:05:15.860 --> 00:05:19.540
and grows out of the particular
individualistic preoccupations

00:05:19.540 --> 00:05:21.970
of American culture as
we suggested last time.

00:05:21.970 --> 00:05:26.360
But also, then becomes a
particularly dramatic instance

00:05:26.360 --> 00:05:28.500
of what we might say the
movies as a whole have

00:05:28.500 --> 00:05:29.790
been in American society.

00:05:29.790 --> 00:05:33.680
Or were in American society,
until the advent of television.

00:05:33.680 --> 00:05:36.610
And that is, each genre,
and then the Western genre

00:05:36.610 --> 00:05:38.810
especially, can be
understood as kind

00:05:38.810 --> 00:05:42.340
of a small inversion
of the larger processes

00:05:42.340 --> 00:05:46.700
that operates in this
consensus system.

00:05:46.700 --> 00:05:48.520
And if you recall
the kinds of things

00:05:48.520 --> 00:05:50.810
we were suggesting last
week about the evolution

00:05:50.810 --> 00:05:55.010
of the Western, what we were
confronting in a certain sense

00:05:55.010 --> 00:06:05.270
was the way in which this
astonishingly protean

00:06:05.270 --> 00:06:08.840
shift-changing mythology
can be altered depending

00:06:08.840 --> 00:06:11.520
on the preoccupations of
the society that wants

00:06:11.520 --> 00:06:13.410
to mobilize the mythology.

00:06:13.410 --> 00:06:15.110
Another way of putting
this is to say,

00:06:15.110 --> 00:06:18.150
the mythology, like the larger
culture, is never fixed.

00:06:18.150 --> 00:06:20.230
It's always in process, right.

00:06:20.230 --> 00:06:23.440
So that when one Western
appears, a kind of conversation

00:06:23.440 --> 00:06:26.390
is going on with all
previous Westerns.

00:06:26.390 --> 00:06:29.510
And maybe with other forms
of discourse as well,

00:06:29.510 --> 00:06:32.650
about the central preoccupations
that are part of the Western.

00:06:32.650 --> 00:06:36.140
I just want to remind you of
the sort of historical scheme

00:06:36.140 --> 00:06:38.520
that I sketched in last
time about the Western,

00:06:38.520 --> 00:06:41.750
so you can recognize the point
at which McCabe &amp; Mrs. Miller

00:06:41.750 --> 00:06:43.930
sort of fits our picture.

00:06:43.930 --> 00:06:45.990
Remember that I
suggested in some degree

00:06:45.990 --> 00:06:50.760
that when the Western as a form
emerges after the '30s, when

00:06:50.760 --> 00:06:54.612
it's mainly are sort of novelty
item, which are singing cowboys

00:06:54.612 --> 00:06:56.070
in it and that sort
of thing-- When

00:06:56.070 --> 00:06:59.740
the classic Western emerges
in 1939 with John Ford's

00:06:59.740 --> 00:07:03.550
film-- what's the
name of the film--

00:07:03.550 --> 00:07:08.400
Stagecoach, the first film
that Ford filmed in Monument

00:07:08.400 --> 00:07:13.160
Valley-- when the age of
the so-called classical age

00:07:13.160 --> 00:07:16.850
of the Western
begins in the 1940s,

00:07:16.850 --> 00:07:20.020
I suggested in that lecture that
the Western's of that period

00:07:20.020 --> 00:07:22.560
had a kind of
imperial dimension.

00:07:22.560 --> 00:07:26.040
That those were the Westerns
that most decisively and fully

00:07:26.040 --> 00:07:30.440
celebrated the white settlers
idea of the manifest destiny

00:07:30.440 --> 00:07:34.560
of the American experiment.

00:07:34.560 --> 00:07:38.502
Which was translated of course
into exterminate the Indians.

00:07:38.502 --> 00:07:39.960
The Indians are
sort of in the way.

00:07:39.960 --> 00:07:42.250
The Westward expansion
of the United States

00:07:42.250 --> 00:07:44.810
was, in many ways, clearly
an imperial and even

00:07:44.810 --> 00:07:46.070
a racist project.

00:07:46.070 --> 00:07:49.330
But in the period of the
1940s, the disturbing elements

00:07:49.330 --> 00:07:51.830
of the mythology were
suppressed or ignored,

00:07:51.830 --> 00:07:53.549
even though they were implicit.

00:07:53.549 --> 00:07:54.590
Why would that have been.

00:07:54.590 --> 00:07:58.042
Well one reason was America
itself was at war in the 1940s.

00:07:58.042 --> 00:08:00.000
And the Western was a
particularly appropriate.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:02.140
It was not the only
vehicle, but it

00:08:02.140 --> 00:08:05.080
was one of the vehicles
in which imperial ideas

00:08:05.080 --> 00:08:10.300
of American destiny
and American identity

00:08:10.300 --> 00:08:13.565
would be articulated
or dramatized.

00:08:13.565 --> 00:08:20.020
And I suggested in the
period of the 1950s,

00:08:20.020 --> 00:08:23.420
this Western form begin
to complicate itself,

00:08:23.420 --> 00:08:25.630
that it became less imperial.

00:08:25.630 --> 00:08:28.390
And that there are
many Western films

00:08:28.390 --> 00:08:31.030
of the 1950s that
actually reflect

00:08:31.030 --> 00:08:33.700
many of the domestic
concerns of that era.

00:08:33.700 --> 00:08:36.630
The generation gap, the
discontent of young people

00:08:36.630 --> 00:08:40.100
growing up into a society that
seem to have no work for them--

00:08:40.100 --> 00:08:41.125
this is the early 1950s.

00:08:44.130 --> 00:08:46.710
And as the decade
goes on and leads

00:08:46.710 --> 00:08:50.680
into the 1960s, an increasing
awareness of racial turmoil

00:08:50.680 --> 00:08:52.110
in the United
States-- so Westerns

00:08:52.110 --> 00:08:55.460
begin to be partly about
juvenile delinquency,

00:08:55.460 --> 00:08:57.230
or about social problems.

00:08:57.230 --> 00:09:00.260
Always filtered, of course,
through the historical lens

00:09:00.260 --> 00:09:01.150
of the Western.

00:09:01.150 --> 00:09:04.890
And I suggested to you that
the great John Ford classic

00:09:04.890 --> 00:09:07.110
Western that we saw last
week, The Searchers,

00:09:07.110 --> 00:09:11.520
had already in the
late '50s began

00:09:11.520 --> 00:09:18.240
to incorporate certain kinds
of subversive questions.

00:09:18.240 --> 00:09:21.200
So the '50s is a
time when the Western

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:24.320
begins to show social problems.

00:09:24.320 --> 00:09:25.730
There's a kind of
inward turning,

00:09:25.730 --> 00:09:28.120
in which the psychological
problems of characters

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:30.060
become important in a new way.

00:09:30.060 --> 00:09:33.720
And then in the '60s, this
questioning of the genre

00:09:33.720 --> 00:09:37.600
proceeds and expands
even more fully.

00:09:37.600 --> 00:09:42.410
And as we suggested, there are
a series of films of Westerns

00:09:42.410 --> 00:09:45.360
in the '60s that, even
more substantially

00:09:45.360 --> 00:09:47.930
than The Searchers, begin
to sort of raise doubts

00:09:47.930 --> 00:09:49.940
about some of the most
fundamental questions

00:09:49.940 --> 00:09:50.740
of the Western.

00:09:50.740 --> 00:09:53.520
And of course, as
the decade wears on,

00:09:53.520 --> 00:09:56.980
there are increasing
encouragements or incitements

00:09:56.980 --> 00:09:59.070
from the larger culture--
from the social history

00:09:59.070 --> 00:10:04.380
of the larger culture-- to
make the Western genre begin

00:10:04.380 --> 00:10:05.190
to question itself.

00:10:05.190 --> 00:10:06.690
And what are those
things that begin

00:10:06.690 --> 00:10:09.200
to happen as the '60s wears on.

00:10:09.200 --> 00:10:10.940
They were embedded
in the '50s but they

00:10:10.940 --> 00:10:12.650
become much more serious.

00:10:12.650 --> 00:10:14.820
The first is racial
turmoil, right.

00:10:14.820 --> 00:10:16.800
The Civil Rights Movement
becomes more and more

00:10:16.800 --> 00:10:18.620
militant through the 1960s.

00:10:18.620 --> 00:10:23.870
And there is real conflict
in the society emerging

00:10:23.870 --> 00:10:26.330
very powerfully.

00:10:26.330 --> 00:10:30.940
And that racial turmoil becomes
more and more militant, more

00:10:30.940 --> 00:10:33.820
and more polarizing
as the decade goes on.

00:10:33.820 --> 00:10:37.090
But what's the other great
terrible fact of the 1960s,

00:10:37.090 --> 00:10:40.210
that explains why American
society was so divided.

00:10:40.210 --> 00:10:41.950
And so uncertain of itself.

00:10:41.950 --> 00:10:44.052
The Vietnam War
of course, right.

00:10:44.052 --> 00:10:45.510
By the end of the
decade, America's

00:10:45.510 --> 00:10:47.290
deeply immersed in Vietnam.

00:10:47.290 --> 00:10:52.280
The college-aged generation
is alienated from its elders.

00:10:52.280 --> 00:10:56.560
There are demonstrations on
campuses in 1967, '68, right.

00:10:56.560 --> 00:10:59.690
And then in 1968, two really
horrific assassinations

00:10:59.690 --> 00:11:04.080
occurred to help mark the 1960s
as a decisively disturbed time

00:11:04.080 --> 00:11:05.250
in American history.

00:11:05.250 --> 00:11:07.850
Who are the two
great figures who die

00:11:07.850 --> 00:11:12.430
and were assassinated in 1968.

00:11:12.430 --> 00:11:19.990
One is Martin Luther King,
the great hero of a peaceful,

00:11:19.990 --> 00:11:24.910
Ghandi-like Civil Rights
Movement is assassinated.

00:11:24.910 --> 00:11:26.960
And that gives it
even stronger impetus

00:11:26.960 --> 00:11:30.900
to the more militant
arguments for civil rights

00:11:30.900 --> 00:11:36.210
that unlike Doctor
King's position,

00:11:36.210 --> 00:11:40.750
did not so it really
embrace nonviolence.

00:11:40.750 --> 00:11:42.980
So the combination
of the Vietnam War

00:11:42.980 --> 00:11:45.510
and the civil rights
movement combining together

00:11:45.510 --> 00:11:49.820
created a tremendous
turmoil in American society.

00:11:49.820 --> 00:11:51.300
And there are many
film historians

00:11:51.300 --> 00:11:56.700
who would say that the totally
subversive genre films,

00:11:56.700 --> 00:12:00.020
the anti-genre films that
emerge in the 1970s-- of which

00:12:00.020 --> 00:12:02.600
the most decisive
example in our course

00:12:02.600 --> 00:12:06.370
is McCabe &amp; Mrs. Miller, so
it completes our argument.

00:12:06.370 --> 00:12:09.290
There are many who would say
that a sufficient explanation

00:12:09.290 --> 00:12:14.890
for the subversion of the genre,
for the fact that the Westerns

00:12:14.890 --> 00:12:17.580
of the '70s-- that some of
the Westerns of the '70s

00:12:17.580 --> 00:12:20.150
and beyond-- in
some sense, could

00:12:20.150 --> 00:12:21.940
be identified as anti Western.

00:12:21.940 --> 00:12:24.770
So hostile are they--
so hostile are they

00:12:24.770 --> 00:12:28.180
to the basic assumptions
of their ancestors,

00:12:28.180 --> 00:12:30.560
so much that they
turn the heroic values

00:12:30.560 --> 00:12:32.180
of their ancestors
on their head.

00:12:32.180 --> 00:12:35.470
And you'll and you'll see a
wonderfully decisive example

00:12:35.470 --> 00:12:37.060
of this in tonight's film.

00:12:37.060 --> 00:12:38.770
There's some social
and film historians

00:12:38.770 --> 00:12:40.440
who would say, well,
the difficulties

00:12:40.440 --> 00:12:43.680
in the outer society-- the
war, the Civil Rights Movement,

00:12:43.680 --> 00:12:45.720
the polarization
of the culture is

00:12:45.720 --> 00:12:49.650
sufficient to explain why
these genres, and especially

00:12:49.650 --> 00:12:52.310
this centrally American
genre the Western,

00:12:52.310 --> 00:12:54.130
would suddenly sort
of turn on itself

00:12:54.130 --> 00:12:58.620
and attack what it had
previously celebrated.

00:12:58.620 --> 00:13:01.990
The notions of
individualistic achievement.

00:13:01.990 --> 00:13:05.080
Notions of violent masculinity.

00:13:05.080 --> 00:13:09.300
One of the best books on the Old
West and on the Western film,

00:13:09.300 --> 00:13:13.600
has the wonderful title
Regeneration through Violence.

00:13:13.600 --> 00:13:14.920
Regeneration through Violence.

00:13:14.920 --> 00:13:17.440
And it does describe
what the classic Western

00:13:17.440 --> 00:13:19.840
seems to believe.

00:13:19.840 --> 00:13:21.530
It's actually a scary idea.

00:13:21.530 --> 00:13:24.650
You might think about how often
this notion has been translated

00:13:24.650 --> 00:13:29.570
into sort of foreign policy
behavior by the United States.

00:13:29.570 --> 00:13:32.416
Again, reinforcing the
importance of these

00:13:32.416 --> 00:13:32.915
mythologies.

00:13:35.810 --> 00:13:37.790
But the social
history of the country

00:13:37.790 --> 00:13:42.930
is not really sufficient fully,
to explain why the movies would

00:13:42.930 --> 00:13:44.350
become so subversive.

00:13:44.350 --> 00:13:46.370
And what's the answer.

00:13:46.370 --> 00:13:49.840
It's implied up here
in number three, right.

00:13:49.840 --> 00:13:51.660
It has to do with the
new consensus medium.

00:13:51.660 --> 00:13:54.310
So let me try to make these
arguments in a slightly more

00:13:54.310 --> 00:13:55.490
systematic way.

00:13:55.490 --> 00:13:58.800
And first, by talking
more concretely

00:13:58.800 --> 00:14:00.430
about the ways in
which the movies

00:14:00.430 --> 00:14:03.070
were different in the 1970s.

00:14:03.070 --> 00:14:05.960
Wherever we look at central
elements of the movies,

00:14:05.960 --> 00:14:10.160
we can see a profound change in
atmosphere and tone and feel.

00:14:10.160 --> 00:14:15.420
The first, if we think about the
sort of characteristic actors

00:14:15.420 --> 00:14:19.030
or acting styles of the
period, and especially

00:14:19.030 --> 00:14:21.610
the characteristic
stars and contrast them

00:14:21.610 --> 00:14:23.700
to the great stars
of the studio era,

00:14:23.700 --> 00:14:25.880
we can get a feel
for how much more

00:14:25.880 --> 00:14:30.480
subversive, problematic,
ironic, anti-heroic, this

00:14:30.480 --> 00:14:32.227
new period in American film is.

00:14:32.227 --> 00:14:34.310
But there are many, many
people who would actually

00:14:34.310 --> 00:14:38.495
say that this moment in American
film is actually one of the--

00:14:38.495 --> 00:14:42.320
and I think I
might say this-- is

00:14:42.320 --> 00:14:44.460
a moment of great
artistic achievement.

00:14:44.460 --> 00:14:47.650
Whatever we would say about the
early '70s and the whole decade

00:14:47.650 --> 00:14:51.220
of the '70s, we could call
it a moment or a period

00:14:51.220 --> 00:14:53.490
of profound transition.

00:14:53.490 --> 00:14:55.730
A great artistic achievement.

00:14:55.730 --> 00:15:01.350
But also, an achievement
gotten at a profound cost.

00:15:01.350 --> 00:15:03.260
A fundamental,
irreversible shift

00:15:03.260 --> 00:15:05.820
in the relation of American
movies to their audience, OK.

00:15:05.820 --> 00:15:07.140
So that's the basic idea.

00:15:07.140 --> 00:15:09.760
But what did this shift look
like, what did it feel like.

00:15:09.760 --> 00:15:15.630
Well, I've suggested that it's
grungier, more ironic, deeply

00:15:15.630 --> 00:15:16.690
anti-heroic.

00:15:16.690 --> 00:15:18.890
And one way I can
capture this is

00:15:18.890 --> 00:15:22.100
by taking a scene from
one of the characteristic,

00:15:22.100 --> 00:15:26.610
really defining actors of the
1970s, of what we might call

00:15:26.610 --> 00:15:30.320
the post-consensus era, the
post-Hollywood era, Jack

00:15:30.320 --> 00:15:31.290
Nicholson.

00:15:31.290 --> 00:15:33.800
I want to show you
what is, in some sense,

00:15:33.800 --> 00:15:35.170
his signature scene.

00:15:35.170 --> 00:15:36.812
And people who
haven't seen Five Easy

00:15:36.812 --> 00:15:40.600
Pieces, where this
fragment comes from,

00:15:40.600 --> 00:15:42.480
know about this scene.

00:15:42.480 --> 00:15:45.030
What I want to propose to
you as you look at this scene

00:15:45.030 --> 00:15:47.510
is think about Jack Nicholson's
behavior in the scene.

00:15:47.510 --> 00:15:51.890
And ask yourself, is it possible
to imagine one of the classic,

00:15:51.890 --> 00:15:57.110
much more dignified heroes--
male protagonists== movie

00:15:57.110 --> 00:16:00.230
stars-- from an earlier era
behaving in the same way.

00:16:00.230 --> 00:16:02.720
Could we imagine John
Wayne behaving this way.

00:16:02.720 --> 00:16:04.390
Or could we imagine
Jimmy Stewart

00:16:04.390 --> 00:16:06.870
behaving this way or
Henry Fonda behaving.

00:16:06.870 --> 00:16:09.320
And of course the answer--
I'm sure as you'll recognize--

00:16:09.320 --> 00:16:10.530
is no.

00:16:10.530 --> 00:16:13.490
Here's the scene then,
from Five Easy Pieces.

00:16:13.490 --> 00:16:16.496
Some people would call it Jack
Nicholson's signature moment.

