00:19:02.960 --> 00:19:04.250
that emerge in this period.

00:19:04.250 --> 00:19:05.510
Warren Beatty.

00:19:05.510 --> 00:19:06.600
Elliot Gould.

00:19:06.600 --> 00:19:07.770
Dustin Hoffman.

00:19:07.770 --> 00:19:09.510
Robert De Niro.

00:19:09.510 --> 00:19:12.314
Fewer female stars
emerge in this period.

00:19:12.314 --> 00:19:13.230
But they're important.

00:19:13.230 --> 00:19:17.290
some of them did begin their
careers around this time.

00:19:17.290 --> 00:19:21.910
And even the actresses
standing in the same sort

00:19:21.910 --> 00:19:31.880
of ironizing and anti-heroic
relation to their ancestors

00:19:31.880 --> 00:19:32.910
as the male actors.

00:19:32.910 --> 00:19:34.620
We might think about
Julie Christie,

00:19:34.620 --> 00:19:38.060
who is the co-star of tonight's
film in McCabe &amp; Mrs. Miller.

00:19:38.060 --> 00:19:39.390
Or Jane Fonda.

00:19:39.390 --> 00:19:44.350
Or the actress Faye Dunaway,
who does such a brilliant job

00:19:44.350 --> 00:19:48.360
in the characteristic
early '70s film, Chinatown.

00:19:48.360 --> 00:19:51.790
And each of these
performers, has,

00:19:51.790 --> 00:19:55.440
as I suggested,
a sort of grungy,

00:19:55.440 --> 00:19:58.780
ironized, non-heroic
relationship

00:19:58.780 --> 00:20:04.320
to the iconic figures
of the Hollywood past.

00:20:04.320 --> 00:20:06.600
And something of
the same thing is

00:20:06.600 --> 00:20:08.250
true about the
kinds of directors

00:20:08.250 --> 00:20:10.630
and the kinds of films that
emerged in this period,

00:20:10.630 --> 00:20:12.030
as well.

00:20:12.030 --> 00:20:13.920
It's the period in
which some directors who

00:20:13.920 --> 00:20:17.290
then became dominant figures
over the next 30 years, Martin

00:20:17.290 --> 00:20:22.740
Scorsese, Roman Polanski,
Alan J. Pakula, Francis Ford

00:20:22.740 --> 00:20:28.120
Coppola, Sam Peckinpah, Altman
himself, Stanley Kubrick.

00:20:28.120 --> 00:20:31.590
All of these really
distinctive, auteurist directors

00:20:31.590 --> 00:20:34.410
emerge decisively
in this period.

00:20:34.410 --> 00:20:37.340
And again, the
films that they make

00:20:37.340 --> 00:20:40.350
have a kind of
personal stamp that

00:20:40.350 --> 00:20:44.020
would not have been
possible in the studio era.

00:20:44.020 --> 00:20:46.350
And of course, what I've
left out of the equation

00:20:46.350 --> 00:20:48.660
in talking about
the transformation

00:20:48.660 --> 00:20:50.730
of American movies,
is the reminder

00:20:50.730 --> 00:20:52.970
that it was in the
period from 1950

00:20:52.970 --> 00:20:55.790
through the late
'60s or early '70s,

00:20:55.790 --> 00:20:58.070
that the apparatus of
the old Hollywood system

00:20:58.070 --> 00:20:59.990
began to break down.

00:20:59.990 --> 00:21:02.890
Movies continued to be
made, but the old studios

00:21:02.890 --> 00:21:05.110
by the end of the '60s
all really dissolved.

00:21:05.110 --> 00:21:09.290
The studios no longer
held contracts for dozens,

00:21:09.290 --> 00:21:14.810
if not hundreds, of actors
and armies of technicians

00:21:14.810 --> 00:21:16.340
and so forth.

00:21:16.340 --> 00:21:18.130
The mass production
system that had

00:21:18.130 --> 00:21:21.530
been characteristic of Hollywood
for most of the 20th century

00:21:21.530 --> 00:21:23.470
had broken down by
the end of the '70s.

00:21:23.470 --> 00:21:25.330
And what movie is
really had become,

00:21:25.330 --> 00:21:27.030
essentially, were deals.

00:21:27.030 --> 00:21:29.990
You've got a bankable
star to agree to a script.

00:21:29.990 --> 00:21:33.094
You get the screenwriter
to agree to do the work.

00:21:33.094 --> 00:21:35.385
You go to the money man and
you say, I've got Nicholson

00:21:35.385 --> 00:21:37.880
and I've got this screenwriter,
how about if we go ahead

00:21:37.880 --> 00:21:38.970
on the movie.

00:21:38.970 --> 00:21:41.900
Very different from the days in
which the studio bosses would

00:21:41.900 --> 00:21:43.600
sit down and say,
we have to produce

00:21:43.600 --> 00:21:45.250
x number of films this year.

00:21:45.250 --> 00:21:48.080
Let's decide how many
Westerns, how many comedies

00:21:48.080 --> 00:21:49.020
we want to make.

00:21:49.020 --> 00:21:52.060
Let's decide how we want to
use Barbara Stanwyck this year,

00:21:52.060 --> 00:21:52.880
that sort of thing.

00:21:52.880 --> 00:21:54.500
That game is all over.

00:21:54.500 --> 00:21:57.330
So that from the
economic circumstances

00:21:57.330 --> 00:22:00.080
and the physical ways
in which movies are made

00:22:00.080 --> 00:22:02.180
have undergone a
transformation, as well.

00:22:02.180 --> 00:22:05.840
Every movie becomes a
kind of major product.

00:22:05.840 --> 00:22:10.929
And even though the studio
names survive beyond the 1960s,

00:22:10.929 --> 00:22:11.720
they're just names.

00:22:11.720 --> 00:22:12.840
They're just labels now.

00:22:12.840 --> 00:22:15.440
They actually no
longer represent

00:22:15.440 --> 00:22:17.820
what they had in the studio era.

00:22:17.820 --> 00:22:20.910
Not only a particular
number of films

00:22:20.910 --> 00:22:22.660
that each studio would
pump out each year,

00:22:22.660 --> 00:22:28.240
but holdings in land
and major movie studios

00:22:28.240 --> 00:22:34.650
with all the supporting
material and personnel

00:22:34.650 --> 00:22:40.130
necessary to run a
systematic operation

00:22:40.130 --> 00:22:41.670
for the mass
production of movies.

00:22:41.670 --> 00:22:47.360
That game is over really
by the time the '70s began.

00:22:48.735 --> 00:22:50.860
And if you actually look
at the physical appearance

00:22:50.860 --> 00:22:52.234
of the actors of
this period, you

00:22:52.234 --> 00:22:53.760
could see that they
look less grand.

00:22:53.760 --> 00:22:54.769
They look less large.

00:22:54.769 --> 00:22:56.310
They literally are
often not as tall.

00:22:56.310 --> 00:22:59.340
Dustin Hoffman's a shrimp,
is even shorter than I am.

00:22:59.340 --> 00:23:01.149
When he acts with
some female stars,

00:23:01.149 --> 00:23:02.940
they have to put him
on a box so it doesn't

00:23:02.940 --> 00:23:04.040
look like he's too small.

00:23:04.040 --> 00:23:06.350
They don't photograph
the box, of course.

00:23:06.350 --> 00:23:09.450
And there's something,
not exactly wimpish,

00:23:09.450 --> 00:23:13.240
but ironic or outlawish,
an unwholesomeness

00:23:13.240 --> 00:23:16.970
over a nervousness or a
sense of explosive anger--

00:23:16.970 --> 00:23:19.500
the Nicholson character is a
wonderful instance of that--

00:23:19.500 --> 00:23:20.360
might emerge.

00:23:20.360 --> 00:23:24.720
These qualities, the instability
of the idea of the hero

00:23:24.720 --> 00:23:28.779
is part of what is
emerging in these periods.

00:23:28.779 --> 00:23:31.070
And I have another clip I
want to show you that I think

00:23:31.070 --> 00:23:32.740
and capture another
part of this.

00:23:32.740 --> 00:23:35.080
It will also
illustrate the new sort

00:23:35.080 --> 00:23:38.990
of grungy type hero
and movie star who

00:23:38.990 --> 00:23:40.184
emerges in this period.

00:23:40.184 --> 00:23:41.850
But it will also tell
you something else

00:23:41.850 --> 00:23:44.400
about the way in which
these transformations

00:23:44.400 --> 00:23:47.980
and subversions were expressed
in films, themselves.

00:23:47.980 --> 00:23:54.360
And this is a clip from the end
of another Robert Altman movie,

00:23:54.360 --> 00:23:56.080
made roughly around
the same time.

00:23:56.080 --> 00:23:57.500
It's also a genre film.

00:23:57.500 --> 00:24:00.770
And like McCabe &amp; Mrs. Miller,
it's a kind of anti-genre film.

00:24:00.770 --> 00:24:03.880
It uses the trappings
of a traditional genre,

00:24:03.880 --> 00:24:06.090
but he turns those
trappings askew

00:24:06.090 --> 00:24:09.630
in ways that make the audience
nervous, in ways that depart,

00:24:09.630 --> 00:24:13.340
from not just the standard
expectations of the genre,

00:24:13.340 --> 00:24:16.390
but even the moral assumptions
that are made by the genre.

00:24:16.390 --> 00:24:18.500
In this case, the
moral assumption

00:24:18.500 --> 00:24:21.430
that is at most decisively
undercut, as you'll see,

00:24:21.430 --> 00:24:25.550
has to do with the moral
rectitude of the hero, himself.

00:24:25.550 --> 00:24:28.010
And this expresses
itself all the way

00:24:28.010 --> 00:24:30.380
through many of these stories
and many of these films,

00:24:30.380 --> 00:24:33.250
but it often expresses itself
with particular clarity

00:24:33.250 --> 00:24:34.705
in the endings of films.

00:24:36.300 --> 00:24:39.012
So watch for the kind of
actor that Elliot Gould

00:24:39.012 --> 00:24:40.470
is, because he's
the star, he plays

00:24:40.470 --> 00:24:42.730
the detective in this sequence.

00:24:42.730 --> 00:24:45.406
I want you to look
now, at the final,

00:24:45.406 --> 00:24:47.030
really sort of the
climactic sequence--

00:24:47.030 --> 00:24:51.530
the dramatic ending-- of
an Altman detective film.

00:24:51.530 --> 00:24:56.520
A remake of a film by the
same title, based on a novel

00:24:56.520 --> 00:25:00.960
by the same title, going
back into the '20s.

00:25:00.960 --> 00:25:06.290
It's a film entitled
The Long Goodbye.

00:25:06.290 --> 00:25:14.890
And it stars Raymond Chandler's
most famous private eye figure.

00:25:14.890 --> 00:25:17.780
This private eye figure had
been played in the past,

00:25:17.780 --> 00:25:24.710
by a series of really, sort
of tough guy, Hollywood leads.

00:25:24.710 --> 00:25:28.510
And in Altman's version
of The Long Goodbye,

00:25:28.510 --> 00:25:31.650
I think Robert Mitchum, in
fact, a very hulk, bulky kind

00:25:31.650 --> 00:25:35.800
of tough, studly kind of actor
had played the role at least

00:25:35.800 --> 00:25:36.950
once, previously.

00:25:36.950 --> 00:25:40.610
In Altman's version of the film,
Elliot Gould plays the roll.

00:25:40.610 --> 00:25:42.780
And Eliot Gould is a
kind of-- as some of you

00:25:42.780 --> 00:25:45.260
know if you've seen
his acting-- is

00:25:45.260 --> 00:25:48.190
an actor for the modern
age in some ways.

00:25:48.190 --> 00:25:50.080
He talks to himself a lot.

00:25:50.080 --> 00:25:54.040
He always a kind of
anti-heroic demeanor.

00:25:54.040 --> 00:25:58.780
So, remember we've said also
that the endings of genre forms

00:25:58.780 --> 00:26:00.520
are often very conventionalized.

00:26:00.520 --> 00:26:02.590
Think about the endings
of situation comedy,

00:26:02.590 --> 00:26:03.530
as an example.

00:26:03.530 --> 00:26:06.520
Or the way in which, at the end
of certain forms of melodrama,

00:26:06.520 --> 00:26:11.100
you expect certain
forms of reassurance.

00:26:11.100 --> 00:26:15.210
That things will work out,
or have worked out, right.

00:26:15.210 --> 00:26:17.900
One of the fundamental
functions of the happy ending

00:26:17.900 --> 00:26:20.910
of most genre forms in the
classic age of Hollywood

00:26:20.910 --> 00:26:24.690
was precisely to return us
to that form of reassurance.

00:26:24.690 --> 00:26:28.640
All right, so here is the
ending of a detective film

00:26:28.640 --> 00:26:31.990
called The Long Goodbye,
starring Elliot Gould.

00:26:31.990 --> 00:26:33.420
And perhaps the
only thing I need

00:26:33.420 --> 00:26:39.330
to do to introduce the
scene, is to simply say

00:26:39.330 --> 00:26:43.792
that the detective's quest
has led him, finally,

00:26:43.792 --> 00:26:46.000
at the end of the film, to
sort of solve the mystery.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:48.920
And he's found the
man who has committed

00:26:48.920 --> 00:26:52.490
the horrendous crimes he's been
investigating through the film.

00:26:52.490 --> 00:26:55.480
And the man turns out to
have been a friend of his,

00:26:55.480 --> 00:26:56.690
someone he has known.

00:26:56.690 --> 00:27:00.370
And in fact, someone who
had taken advantage of him.

00:27:00.370 --> 00:27:02.676
And here's the very
end of the film.

