00:28:58.370 --> 00:28:59.703
DAVID THORBURN: Pretty shocking.

00:28:59.703 --> 00:29:03.520
The hero of the movie--
the protagonist-- the guy

00:29:03.520 --> 00:29:05.380
we identify with
all the way through

00:29:05.380 --> 00:29:07.440
commits cold-blooded murder.

00:29:07.440 --> 00:29:09.962
He's a vigilante-- commits
cold blooded murder

00:29:09.962 --> 00:29:10.920
at the end of the film.

00:29:10.920 --> 00:29:12.253
And that is the end of the film.

00:29:12.253 --> 00:29:14.060
He gets away with it.

00:29:14.060 --> 00:29:16.532
So there is a kind
of justice done

00:29:16.532 --> 00:29:18.490
at the end of the film
in a kind of narrow way,

00:29:18.490 --> 00:29:20.323
because the murderer
is caught and punished.

00:29:22.960 --> 00:29:24.800
And incidentally,
this violates what

00:29:24.800 --> 00:29:26.450
happens in the original novel.

00:29:26.450 --> 00:29:28.440
It violates what happens
in the first film

00:29:28.440 --> 00:29:30.970
version of the novel.

00:29:30.970 --> 00:29:33.700
But think what happens
to genre forms,

00:29:33.700 --> 00:29:36.150
not only when the hero
or the protagonist

00:29:36.150 --> 00:29:39.710
becomes grungy ironic and
anti-heroic in his behavior

00:29:39.710 --> 00:29:41.730
and demeanor.

00:29:41.730 --> 00:29:45.820
And then when the story itself
begins to undermine the deepest

00:29:45.820 --> 00:29:47.890
assumptions about
heroism and righteous

00:29:47.890 --> 00:29:54.145
behavior that seem to justify
or undergird these endings.

00:29:55.890 --> 00:29:57.730
But in a way, one
could say it's a happy

00:29:57.730 --> 00:30:03.020
ending if one has a very
austere notion of justice.

00:30:03.020 --> 00:30:05.070
An almost inhuman
notion of justice.

00:30:05.070 --> 00:30:07.000
But what about this
protagonist who

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:11.400
does his own vigilante justice.

00:30:11.400 --> 00:30:16.930
And when the film
first appeared--

00:30:16.930 --> 00:30:19.170
it's impossible to
exaggerate the effect

00:30:19.170 --> 00:30:20.265
this shocking and had.

00:30:22.840 --> 00:30:24.590
One reason it's so
shocking of course,

00:30:24.590 --> 00:30:28.650
is that the generic
expectations run so totally

00:30:28.650 --> 00:30:31.580
in the opposite direction-- that
the most cold blooded murder

00:30:31.580 --> 00:30:33.820
in the film should be the
character with whom you've

00:30:33.820 --> 00:30:35.440
identified all the way through.

00:30:35.440 --> 00:30:37.400
Who is supposed to
be solving the crime

00:30:37.400 --> 00:30:40.860
and bringing evil to
justice should turn out

00:30:40.860 --> 00:30:44.340
to be evil himself in such
a shocking and brutal way

00:30:44.340 --> 00:30:48.690
undermines some of the most
up the basic assumptions

00:30:48.690 --> 00:30:50.490
you make about
the kind of safety

00:30:50.490 --> 00:30:52.620
that the genre of
the detective story

00:30:52.620 --> 00:30:54.550
seems to afford to its viewer.

00:30:54.550 --> 00:30:56.910
And this is not an
isolated instance,

00:30:56.910 --> 00:31:00.150
as you'll see in tonight's film.

00:31:00.150 --> 00:31:03.960
Altman does almost exactly the
same thing with the Western

00:31:03.960 --> 00:31:07.740
that he does in The Long
Goodbye to the detective story.

00:31:07.740 --> 00:31:11.380
I'll return tonight to
say a little bit more

00:31:11.380 --> 00:31:14.210
about the particular ways
in which McCabe &amp; Mrs.

00:31:14.210 --> 00:31:23.070
Miller embodies this notion
I've been suggesting to you.

00:31:23.070 --> 00:31:28.450
Embodies the anti-generic
or subversive principles

00:31:28.450 --> 00:31:30.300
of the kinds of
movies that begin

00:31:30.300 --> 00:31:36.290
to emerge at the end of
the '60s and in the 1970s.

00:31:36.290 --> 00:31:39.310
Well I've already talked to
you about the social history

00:31:39.310 --> 00:31:42.970
of the '60s and '70s.

00:31:42.970 --> 00:31:45.330
And I don't want
to repeat myself,

00:31:45.330 --> 00:31:48.070
but there were some things that
I left out in my quick account

00:31:48.070 --> 00:31:48.570
earlier.

00:31:48.570 --> 00:31:50.960
So let's return
briefly to remember

00:31:50.960 --> 00:31:52.550
the sequence of presidents.

00:31:52.550 --> 00:31:56.470
Because of course, the sequence
of presidents-- Kennedy,

00:31:56.470 --> 00:31:59.460
who was assassinated in
the early '60s, right.

00:31:59.460 --> 00:32:02.230
Already, the social fabric
in the United States

00:32:02.230 --> 00:32:03.750
was frayed to the
point of breaking

00:32:03.750 --> 00:32:05.147
by the end of the '60s.

00:32:05.147 --> 00:32:06.980
Those of us who lived
through it will always

00:32:06.980 --> 00:32:12.190
remember it as an
astonishingly polarized time.

00:32:12.190 --> 00:32:16.500
And in the progression from
Kennedy to Johnson to Nixon,

00:32:16.500 --> 00:32:18.220
there is a social
history in which

00:32:18.220 --> 00:32:23.090
that change in the society
is of course, implied.

00:32:23.090 --> 00:32:27.310
And of course, it concludes in
a way, with the terrible event

00:32:27.310 --> 00:32:30.870
of the Watergate scandal--
the Watergate investigations--

00:32:30.870 --> 00:32:32.750
in which for the first
time in our history,

00:32:32.750 --> 00:32:34.480
a sitting president resigned.

00:32:34.480 --> 00:32:38.000
And so you can see that the
outward social-- and of course,

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:41.330
the Watergate
scandal raised doubts

00:32:41.330 --> 00:32:44.730
about the probity and
decency of the highest

00:32:44.730 --> 00:32:46.060
officers of our government.

00:32:46.060 --> 00:32:48.830
And while that might
not seem so surprising

00:32:48.830 --> 00:32:54.880
in the age of-- I have to
avoid offending some of you--

00:32:54.880 --> 00:32:58.710
in our current situation,
where it isn't that

00:32:58.710 --> 00:33:01.720
difficult to doubt what we're
told by our government leaders,

00:33:01.720 --> 00:33:04.700
it's important to
recognize that-- not

00:33:04.700 --> 00:33:06.870
that this was a new
experience for Americans,

00:33:06.870 --> 00:33:09.070
governments always
lie-- but there really

00:33:09.070 --> 00:33:12.850
was a sense of disillusionment
with the fundamental structures

00:33:12.850 --> 00:33:14.770
of the society
that was emerging.

00:33:14.770 --> 00:33:16.390
Because of the Civil
Rights Movement.

00:33:16.390 --> 00:33:19.620
Then because of the well
because of the war in Vietnam.

00:33:22.340 --> 00:33:27.560
And then also, as
a kind of icing

00:33:27.560 --> 00:33:30.840
on the cake in a certain sense,
a kind of terrible addition

00:33:30.840 --> 00:33:34.440
to this weakening the
country, but strengthening

00:33:34.440 --> 00:33:37.490
this sense of polarization
and disturbances, if nothing

00:33:37.490 --> 00:33:38.220
can be trusted.

00:33:38.220 --> 00:33:40.650
As if our structures
are falling apart

00:33:40.650 --> 00:33:44.180
or are endangered in some way
was the fact the president,

00:33:44.180 --> 00:33:46.960
in effect resigned, rather
than face impeachment.

00:33:46.960 --> 00:33:51.880
Because of his behavior
in the Watergate business.

00:33:51.880 --> 00:33:54.514
So the highest
levels of government

00:33:54.514 --> 00:33:56.930
and the fundamental structures
of government were in play.

00:33:56.930 --> 00:34:00.400
And it would obviously, in such
a time, it's not inappropriate.

00:34:00.400 --> 00:34:03.440
You would expect the central
story forms of a culture

00:34:03.440 --> 00:34:05.530
to reflect some disturbance.

00:34:05.530 --> 00:34:08.110
But why is it not
sufficient simply

00:34:08.110 --> 00:34:11.250
to urge this social
history argument?

00:34:11.250 --> 00:34:13.230
To explain what
happened to movies?

00:34:13.230 --> 00:34:15.000
The simplest answer
is, if you look

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:17.330
at what was on television
at the same time,

00:34:17.330 --> 00:34:20.679
you can certainly see television
becoming more complex.

00:34:20.679 --> 00:34:22.370
In fact, the late
'60s and early '70s

00:34:22.370 --> 00:34:25.070
are a transforming moment
for television, as well.

00:34:25.070 --> 00:34:27.949
Partly because that's the moment
when television consciously

00:34:27.949 --> 00:34:31.147
realized that it has a more
central place in the society

00:34:31.147 --> 00:34:31.980
than the movies did.

00:34:31.980 --> 00:34:34.120
It had, for awhile,
already achieved this.

00:34:34.120 --> 00:34:37.150
But no one on either side of
the divide fully recognized it.

00:34:37.150 --> 00:34:39.420
But by the late
'60s and early '70s,

00:34:39.420 --> 00:34:41.480
American television
now knows itself

00:34:41.480 --> 00:34:44.199
to be the central medium
of consensus narrative.

00:34:44.199 --> 00:34:46.489
The society recognizes
that the changes occur.

00:34:46.489 --> 00:34:48.449
I don't mean that
legislation is passed,

00:34:48.449 --> 00:34:51.570
I mean this understanding slowly
dawns over a period of time,

00:34:51.570 --> 00:34:52.070
right.

00:34:52.070 --> 00:34:54.889
And there was a great
sense among filmmakers

00:34:54.889 --> 00:34:56.020
of liberation and freedom.

00:34:56.020 --> 00:34:57.394
And they're not
wrong about that.

00:34:57.394 --> 00:34:59.650
I mean, one might
argue that the '70s

00:34:59.650 --> 00:35:02.630
is the greatest decade of all in
the history of American movies.

00:35:02.630 --> 00:35:06.280
So many remarkable films
were made in that time.

00:35:06.280 --> 00:35:08.270
And surely, one of
the reasons for it

00:35:08.270 --> 00:35:11.060
was film was liberated
from the necessity

00:35:11.060 --> 00:35:13.260
to embrace what
we're ultimately,

00:35:13.260 --> 00:35:15.340
although very
generous principles,

00:35:15.340 --> 00:35:17.870
they were still in the end,
conservative principles.

00:35:17.870 --> 00:35:21.280
About how a story in a consensus
medium can be told, right.

00:35:23.300 --> 00:35:32.090
But the reason that the
social history argument

00:35:32.090 --> 00:35:35.376
is insufficient for explaining
the way movies changed,

00:35:35.376 --> 00:35:36.750
is that if you
look at television

00:35:36.750 --> 00:35:39.850
you could state a
story system that's

00:35:39.850 --> 00:35:42.960
telling stories that are more
complex, and more ironized,

00:35:42.960 --> 00:35:45.240
and do raise certain
kinds of questions

00:35:45.240 --> 00:35:46.950
about the social and
political order that

00:35:46.950 --> 00:35:50.430
might be thought to be
disturbing, and even

00:35:50.430 --> 00:35:51.890
potentially subversive.

00:35:51.890 --> 00:35:53.990
But on television,
the center holds.

00:35:53.990 --> 00:35:56.030
On television, the
endings remain happy,

00:35:56.030 --> 00:35:58.790
or at least reassuring, mostly.

00:35:58.790 --> 00:36:02.270
On television, some of the very
same genre forms, especially

00:36:02.270 --> 00:36:05.710
detective and cop shows,
are all over the place.

00:36:05.710 --> 00:36:07.190
The fables of law and order.

00:36:07.190 --> 00:36:09.520
Fables of injustice.

00:36:09.520 --> 00:36:11.610
And the stories that are
being told on television

00:36:11.610 --> 00:36:14.640
do not have the
subversive, completely,

00:36:14.640 --> 00:36:17.740
anti-generic energies that
we're being told on television.

00:36:17.740 --> 00:36:18.530
Why not?

00:36:18.530 --> 00:36:21.190
And again, my
answer is the movies

00:36:21.190 --> 00:36:23.450
have been supplanted
by television.

00:36:23.450 --> 00:36:26.530
That consensus role is now
being played by television.

00:36:26.530 --> 00:36:33.420
And one, quite, I think,
truly dramatic way

00:36:33.420 --> 00:36:37.800
in which we can recognize
this development is

00:36:37.800 --> 00:36:42.700
to talk about the differences
between the movie version

00:36:42.700 --> 00:36:46.290
and the television version of
another Robert Altman text.

00:36:46.290 --> 00:36:52.160
One of his distinctive films
of the 1970s, the movie, MASH.

00:36:52.160 --> 00:36:54.700
How many of you have
seen Altman's MASH?

00:36:54.700 --> 00:36:56.980
Only two, three, not very many.

00:36:59.030 --> 00:37:00.430
But it's a significant film.

00:37:00.430 --> 00:37:04.480
Not as remarkable, I
think, in its full shape

00:37:04.480 --> 00:37:07.910
as the film you're
going to see tonight.

00:37:07.910 --> 00:37:10.040
But a very, very
remarkable film.

00:37:10.040 --> 00:37:12.700
How many of you have seem
the television show, MASH.

00:37:12.700 --> 00:37:13.850
A much larger number.

00:37:13.850 --> 00:37:16.590
But still, for an
American environment,

00:37:16.590 --> 00:37:17.660
a very small number.

00:37:17.660 --> 00:37:22.520
Especially because the show was
on for, in its original run,

00:37:22.520 --> 00:37:25.059
for something-- I
forgot-- like 11 years.

00:37:25.059 --> 00:37:27.350
It's one of the longest
running shows American history.

00:37:27.350 --> 00:37:29.150
And then of course,
it was in re-run

00:37:29.150 --> 00:37:31.330
for more than a decade
in virtually every market

00:37:31.330 --> 00:37:32.490
in the United States.

00:37:32.490 --> 00:37:37.270
So there's hardly anyone
over the age of probably 15

00:37:37.270 --> 00:37:38.950
or 20 in the United
States who hasn't

00:37:38.950 --> 00:37:41.570
seen many episodes of MASH.

00:37:41.570 --> 00:37:44.530
So it's somewhat surprising
that only a minority of you

00:37:44.530 --> 00:37:45.080
have seen it.

00:37:45.080 --> 00:37:49.520
But we can take the difference
between the television version

00:37:49.520 --> 00:37:52.950
of that story and
the movie version

00:37:52.950 --> 00:37:55.180
as a kind of emblem
for this transformation

00:37:55.180 --> 00:37:56.480
that I've been talking about.

00:37:56.480 --> 00:37:59.410
And you don't have to seen
either of the films fully

00:37:59.410 --> 00:38:01.930
to see what I have in mind.

00:38:03.970 --> 00:38:06.710
Elliot Gould, the character
that you saw just a moment

00:38:06.710 --> 00:38:09.870
to go in the clip
from The Long Goodbye,

00:38:09.870 --> 00:38:14.150
is one of the central
doctors in the movie.

00:38:14.150 --> 00:38:17.330
And the other doctor,
the partner doctor,

00:38:17.330 --> 00:38:21.900
characters that are played by
Alan Alda and a comrade, who

00:38:21.900 --> 00:38:24.180
changes over the
course of the full run

00:38:24.180 --> 00:38:25.540
of the show in the series.

00:38:27.030 --> 00:38:29.040
Elliot Gould plays that
character in the movies

00:38:29.040 --> 00:38:33.200
and his partner-- also
varies in the film--

00:38:33.200 --> 00:38:36.890
but his most decisive
partner is Donald Sutherland.

00:38:36.890 --> 00:38:38.830
And Donald Sutherland
is another of these sort

00:38:38.830 --> 00:38:41.590
of ironic, anti-heroic actors.

00:38:43.260 --> 00:38:45.230
They're often actors
whose diction is odd.

00:38:45.230 --> 00:38:47.650
They mumble and they
swallow their words.

00:38:47.650 --> 00:38:49.220
They're sometimes
literally harder

00:38:49.220 --> 00:38:54.960
to hear than their
elocutionarily superior--

00:38:54.960 --> 00:39:02.882
bad adverb-- than their
better spoken ancestors

00:39:02.882 --> 00:39:04.215
in the classic age of Hollywood.

00:39:06.180 --> 00:39:10.010
The movie MASH came
out in 1970 and it

00:39:10.010 --> 00:39:13.030
was a kind of disguised
Vietnam fable,

00:39:13.030 --> 00:39:18.040
it was officially
based on a novel

00:39:18.040 --> 00:39:21.340
describing a MASH
unit-- a medical unit--

00:39:21.340 --> 00:39:22.790
in the Korean War.

00:39:22.790 --> 00:39:25.490
And the movie dealt with the
Korean War too, ostensibly.

00:39:25.490 --> 00:39:28.580
But it was clearly a
metaphor for the current war

00:39:28.580 --> 00:39:29.450
that we were in.

00:39:29.450 --> 00:39:32.470
And the doctors, especially
the two central characters

00:39:32.470 --> 00:39:36.150
played by Elliot Gould
and Donald Sutherland,

00:39:36.150 --> 00:39:38.840
are unbelievably
subversive figures.

00:39:38.840 --> 00:39:41.270
They take their energies
more from the counterculture

00:39:41.270 --> 00:39:43.280
than they do from
any other source.

00:39:43.280 --> 00:39:45.850
They have no respect
for authority at all.

00:39:45.850 --> 00:39:50.600
They engage in forms of
subversive monkey business, all

00:39:50.600 --> 00:39:55.200
the way through the
Altman version of MASH.

00:39:55.200 --> 00:39:58.380
When the movie is translated
a year or two later,

00:39:58.380 --> 00:40:01.900
still while the Vietnam War is
on-- onto American television

00:40:01.900 --> 00:40:03.700
in 1972, I guess--

00:40:03.700 --> 00:40:06.540
And the series are oddly
quite a lot different.

00:40:06.540 --> 00:40:10.480
It does still mobilize certain
anti-war sentiments, of course.

00:40:11.940 --> 00:40:14.700
But, the television
program-- which

00:40:14.700 --> 00:40:17.060
I think in an artistic
sense is probably

00:40:17.060 --> 00:40:18.850
over the long run
of its series better

00:40:18.850 --> 00:40:21.470
than the movie for
all kinds of reasons,

00:40:21.470 --> 00:40:24.630
partly because the characters
evolve and change over time

00:40:24.630 --> 00:40:27.840
in the series in a way that
could not in the movie--

00:40:27.840 --> 00:40:29.540
but the most decisive
thing about it

00:40:29.540 --> 00:40:36.610
is that the television series
retains some of the qualities

00:40:36.610 --> 00:40:40.410
that we associate with
an anti-genre form.

00:40:40.410 --> 00:40:43.100
There are subversive
implications in it, for sure.

00:40:43.100 --> 00:40:46.330
But the center holds in
the television version.

00:40:46.330 --> 00:40:47.344
Why?

00:40:47.344 --> 00:40:49.010
When I say the center
holds, what I mean

00:40:49.010 --> 00:40:53.060
is that the remains in the
film are respect for the larger

00:40:53.060 --> 00:40:55.570
structures of authority
and order in a society,

00:40:55.570 --> 00:40:59.156
however antic and subversive
the doctors might behave

00:40:59.156 --> 00:41:00.280
in any particular instance.

00:41:05.192 --> 00:41:08.950
The literal behavior of the
characters is often less grungy

00:41:08.950 --> 00:41:14.480
and doesn't work with
pornography on the television

00:41:14.480 --> 00:41:16.797
show as it does in the movie.

00:41:16.797 --> 00:41:18.630
I don't mean that the
movie is pornographic,

00:41:18.630 --> 00:41:21.310
but it's much more overt
about sexual matters

00:41:21.310 --> 00:41:24.680
than the more than the
television series is.

00:41:24.680 --> 00:41:27.130
And one of the best ways
one can see the contrast

00:41:27.130 --> 00:41:30.320
is to contrast an actor
like Alan Alda with an actor

00:41:30.320 --> 00:41:31.160
like Elliot Gould.

00:41:31.160 --> 00:41:37.760
There's something dark and
grungy and self-reflective,

00:41:37.760 --> 00:41:43.340
self-aware about
Elliot Gould that one

00:41:43.340 --> 00:41:44.480
doesn't feel about Alda.

00:41:44.480 --> 00:41:47.850
Alda is much easier in his
skin than Elliot Gould.

00:41:47.850 --> 00:41:49.790
One feels about Elliot
Gould as about many

00:41:49.790 --> 00:41:53.177
of the actors that emerges--
dominant stars in the '70s

00:41:53.177 --> 00:41:54.760
and beyond-- is that
they're afflicted

00:41:54.760 --> 00:41:57.170
by a kind of cosmic anxiety.

00:41:57.170 --> 00:42:00.900
That they're anxious figures,
that they're figures of damage,

00:42:00.900 --> 00:42:02.620
in some way.

00:42:02.620 --> 00:42:04.860
Warren Beatty is such
an actor in many ways.

00:42:04.860 --> 00:42:08.040
He's the star of tonight's
film, McCabe &amp; Mrs. Miller.

00:42:08.040 --> 00:42:10.960
There's a particularly
wonderful film of the 1970s

00:42:10.960 --> 00:42:13.870
that I also want to mention
to you after I complete

00:42:13.870 --> 00:42:15.360
my discourse about MASH.

00:42:15.360 --> 00:42:19.870
So these two versions of MASH
then, sort of dramatize for us,

00:42:19.870 --> 00:42:25.050
not that television becomes--
especially by 1970-- simply

00:42:25.050 --> 00:42:27.170
a reactionary medium
that just repeats

00:42:27.170 --> 00:42:30.000
what the ruling class in the
United States wants to say.

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:32.290
It's a much more complicated
medium than that.

00:42:32.290 --> 00:42:34.510
But it is a consensus medium.

00:42:34.510 --> 00:42:38.730
It understands that
it operates according

00:42:38.730 --> 00:42:41.640
to certain unwritten rules
that the society, as a whole,

00:42:41.640 --> 00:42:42.580
has accepted.

00:42:42.580 --> 00:42:45.730
And one of those rules is
that in a consensus medium,

00:42:45.730 --> 00:42:52.710
you can mobilize all kinds
doubts, and dubieties,

00:42:52.710 --> 00:42:56.440
and ironic perspectives
on the larger culture

00:42:56.440 --> 00:42:58.280
are on the central
values of the culture.

00:42:58.280 --> 00:43:00.390
But you can't repudiate
them completely.

00:43:00.390 --> 00:43:03.660
You can't let people come out
of a consensus medium thinking

00:43:03.660 --> 00:43:05.522
that the society
is totally corrupt.

00:43:05.522 --> 00:43:06.980
That there's no
hope for the world.

00:43:10.160 --> 00:43:12.820
Consensus systems
won't allow that.

00:43:12.820 --> 00:43:15.510
They have a comes a kind
of aesthetic and political

00:43:15.510 --> 00:43:17.970
conservatism built into them.

00:43:17.970 --> 00:43:20.990
And the movie MASH
shows how free it

00:43:20.990 --> 00:43:22.840
is of those consensus values.

00:43:22.840 --> 00:43:26.070
The television show
MASH, on the contrary,

00:43:26.070 --> 00:43:28.990
demonstrates how much pressure
a particular genre may

00:43:28.990 --> 00:43:34.910
receive and still remain, in
some sense, a consensus form.

00:43:34.910 --> 00:43:38.300
And it seems to me,
there are many arguments

00:43:38.300 --> 00:43:39.760
to be made for
the idea that MASH

00:43:39.760 --> 00:43:42.890
is one of the most distinctive
artistic achievements

00:43:42.890 --> 00:43:44.090
of American television.

00:43:44.090 --> 00:43:46.590
That it represents
the culmination,

00:43:46.590 --> 00:43:48.680
in some sense of
series traditions

00:43:48.680 --> 00:43:51.770
that go back almost 30 years
by the time MASH appears.

00:43:53.220 --> 00:43:56.070
But what gives it its
real authority and power

00:43:56.070 --> 00:43:59.110
is that incorporates
into itself a subject

00:43:59.110 --> 00:44:01.450
matter that, before
the mid '60s,

00:44:01.450 --> 00:44:03.650
anyway had never been
on television before.

00:44:03.650 --> 00:44:06.700
So it's not that the television
that appears in the late '60s

00:44:06.700 --> 00:44:08.930
early '70s is
trivial or foolish,

00:44:08.930 --> 00:44:12.510
it's just that it is
constrained by these consensus

00:44:12.510 --> 00:44:20.090
principles that no longer
constrain the American movie.

00:44:20.090 --> 00:44:21.820
And when we look
at tonight's film,

00:44:21.820 --> 00:44:23.860
you'll see very decisive
examples of this.

00:44:23.860 --> 00:44:28.860
And I'm excited about how
clearly McCabe &amp; Mrs. Miller

00:44:28.860 --> 00:44:31.200
will crystallize the
kinds of things I've been

00:44:31.200 --> 00:44:33.780
saying to you this afternoon.

00:44:33.780 --> 00:44:40.720
Now I also want to mention
this other example.

00:44:40.720 --> 00:44:42.120
A film I meant to
mention earlier

00:44:42.120 --> 00:44:46.280
when I was going through these
notions about the way in which

00:44:46.280 --> 00:44:48.760
we have different
kinds of directors,

00:44:48.760 --> 00:44:51.890
different kinds of actors,
different kinds of endings,

00:44:51.890 --> 00:44:52.390
right.

00:44:52.390 --> 00:44:54.280
Which means that the
style of the movies

00:44:54.280 --> 00:44:55.620
is often different, as well.

00:44:55.620 --> 00:44:57.610
The visual texture
of the film is--

00:44:57.610 --> 00:45:01.240
they favor jump cuts
and discontinuity tricks

00:45:01.240 --> 00:45:03.590
much more than the classic
Hollywood movie does.

00:45:03.590 --> 00:45:05.950
And the film I wanted
to tell you about

00:45:05.950 --> 00:45:07.655
is a film-- I meant
to mention earlier

00:45:07.655 --> 00:45:09.380
and I'll conclude
today's lecture

00:45:09.380 --> 00:45:12.840
with sort of another example,
like the examples I've

00:45:12.840 --> 00:45:15.970
given so far-- in
which what we get

00:45:15.970 --> 00:45:18.610
is it a profoundly
subversive film.

00:45:18.610 --> 00:45:22.180
Whose presence would have been
impossible five years earlier,

00:45:22.180 --> 00:45:24.760
or 10 years earlier, when
the movies were still

00:45:24.760 --> 00:45:28.070
performing their consensus
function in American society.

00:45:28.070 --> 00:45:31.120
The film I'm thinking about as
a film by the director, Alan J

00:45:31.120 --> 00:45:36.510
Pakula, some people
call him Alan Peculiar,

00:45:36.510 --> 00:45:38.280
called The Parallax View.

00:45:38.280 --> 00:45:40.010
Any of you seen
The Parallax View?

00:45:40.010 --> 00:45:44.840
It's one of the great films
of this early '70s period.

00:45:44.840 --> 00:45:48.260
And it's a conspiracy
fantasy film.

00:45:52.510 --> 00:45:57.680
Warren Beatty plays the central
character in the film, a drunk.

00:45:57.680 --> 00:46:01.640
And fact that he's a drunkard
and radically imperfect person,

00:46:01.640 --> 00:46:03.610
is also characteristic
of the kinds

00:46:03.610 --> 00:46:07.260
of heroes-- a protagonist--
that we begin to see in the '70s

00:46:07.260 --> 00:46:08.090
and beyond.

00:46:08.090 --> 00:46:10.800
Radically imperfect
protagonists begin

00:46:10.800 --> 00:46:15.160
to become much more the
norm in American movies

00:46:15.160 --> 00:46:18.070
after the Hollywood
system has declined.

00:46:18.070 --> 00:46:21.640
Well in this film,
Warren Beatty plays

00:46:21.640 --> 00:46:24.380
a recovered
alcoholic journalist,

00:46:24.380 --> 00:46:27.490
who has been fired from a
series of important jobs

00:46:27.490 --> 00:46:30.450
and is now working
for a minor newspaper

00:46:30.450 --> 00:46:32.260
in Seattle, Washington.

00:46:32.260 --> 00:46:33.660
His name is Frady.

00:46:33.660 --> 00:46:37.820
F-R-A-I-D-Y, I think,
or maybe it's F-R-A-D-Y,

00:46:37.820 --> 00:46:40.760
but it's supposed
to echo afraid.

00:46:40.760 --> 00:46:43.116
He's like a fraidy cat.

00:46:43.116 --> 00:46:45.240
you're supposed to sort of
partly feel in the film.

00:46:45.240 --> 00:46:50.240
And with the help of
a newspaper editor

00:46:50.240 --> 00:46:53.910
he works for, he
stumbles upon what

00:46:53.910 --> 00:46:56.780
turns out to be a vast
political conspiracy.

00:46:56.780 --> 00:46:58.970
He's actually present in
the beginning of the film,

00:46:58.970 --> 00:47:02.510
at what looks like
a random killing

00:47:02.510 --> 00:47:04.280
of a political candidate.

00:47:04.280 --> 00:47:06.152
Begins to investigate,
he discovers in fact,

00:47:06.152 --> 00:47:07.720
that there was
probably conspiracy.

00:47:07.720 --> 00:47:10.610
The candidate was assassinated.

00:47:10.610 --> 00:47:16.050
And then he goes
undercover and he engages

00:47:16.050 --> 00:47:17.660
in a long investigation.

00:47:17.660 --> 00:47:20.450
The shape of the film, and
the energies of the film,

00:47:20.450 --> 00:47:23.620
are very like dozens of films
we've seen earlier, especially

00:47:23.620 --> 00:47:24.840
during the Hollywood era.

00:47:24.840 --> 00:47:28.590
In which a lone hero,
discovering terrible facts that

00:47:28.590 --> 00:47:34.010
are dangerous to his
community or his society,

00:47:34.010 --> 00:47:35.780
shows the courage
and the fortitude

00:47:35.780 --> 00:47:39.700
and the end resilience,
and the focus,

00:47:39.700 --> 00:47:41.570
to follow through
and solve the mystery

00:47:41.570 --> 00:47:43.010
and then save the world.

00:47:43.010 --> 00:47:45.930
In the most elaborate versions
of this fantasy, what's

00:47:45.930 --> 00:47:48.880
at stake is the fate of the
world or the fate of a society.

00:47:48.880 --> 00:47:52.720
In smaller versions, it might
be something somewhat less.

00:47:52.720 --> 00:47:54.320
And that's what
it turns out here.

00:47:54.320 --> 00:47:55.800
He penetrates into
this conspiracy

00:47:55.800 --> 00:47:57.820
and there are allusions
and references

00:47:57.820 --> 00:47:59.990
that make you-- especially
at the end of the film--

00:47:59.990 --> 00:48:05.030
associate the conspiracy with
the Kennedy assassination.

00:48:05.030 --> 00:48:09.430
There is, in the film then,
a kind of ongoing process

00:48:09.430 --> 00:48:12.760
in which the full nature of the
conspiracy begins to emerge.

00:48:12.760 --> 00:48:15.050
And in fact, it is
an unbelievable.

00:48:15.050 --> 00:48:17.860
If you actually saw
the world in that way

00:48:17.860 --> 00:48:21.070
you probably couldn't even
get a job in the White House.

00:48:21.070 --> 00:48:21.610
I'm sorry.

00:48:23.120 --> 00:48:27.220
But said it's really an
unbelievably conspiratorial

00:48:27.220 --> 00:48:32.280
film, in which it turns out
that there are a sort of network

00:48:32.280 --> 00:48:34.970
of corporate controllers
who are sort of, in effect,

00:48:34.970 --> 00:48:37.160
taking over the government
of the United States.

00:48:37.160 --> 00:48:40.260
And they have unbelievable
power nobody knows-- but anyway.

00:48:40.260 --> 00:48:42.720
This detective has
finally uncovered the plot

00:48:42.720 --> 00:48:44.030
and watch him do it.

00:48:44.030 --> 00:48:46.090
And as the film comes
to its conclusion, what

00:48:46.090 --> 00:48:47.380
do we expect will happen?

00:48:47.380 --> 00:48:50.550
What's the normal
expectation in such a film?

00:48:50.550 --> 00:48:53.490
That his revelations
will save the day, right.

00:48:53.490 --> 00:48:55.530
Well in the very final
sequences of this film,

00:48:55.530 --> 00:48:58.930
we see what looks like a kind
of revelation scene, in which

00:48:58.930 --> 00:49:04.674
our character, Frady,
is in a convention hall

00:49:04.674 --> 00:49:06.840
where they're about to hold
the political nominating

00:49:06.840 --> 00:49:07.780
convention in fact.

00:49:07.780 --> 00:49:11.240
It's very resonant because
the conspirators are trying

00:49:11.240 --> 00:49:14.420
to control that space as well.

00:49:14.420 --> 00:49:17.340
And essentially, he
starts chasing a bad guy,

00:49:17.340 --> 00:49:21.450
being chased by a bad
guy, without going

00:49:21.450 --> 00:49:24.390
into any detail-- I'll spoil the
film for you a little in a way,

00:49:24.390 --> 00:49:26.470
I must-- guess what happens.

00:49:26.470 --> 00:49:27.720
Our hero is killed at the end.

00:49:29.180 --> 00:49:31.930
And the film ends with the
idea that the conspiracy

00:49:31.930 --> 00:49:33.760
is enforced.

00:49:33.760 --> 00:49:36.070
That there's been no change.

00:49:36.070 --> 00:49:39.220
So, it would have been
a disturbing film,

00:49:39.220 --> 00:49:41.430
even if it had ended with
the requisite happy ending

00:49:41.430 --> 00:49:42.450
and a reassuring ending.

00:49:43.930 --> 00:49:47.820
And in and how many films does
the great hero, the character

00:49:47.820 --> 00:49:49.660
you've been following
all the way through,

00:49:49.660 --> 00:49:52.470
who's supposed to be one
in which you've invested

00:49:52.470 --> 00:49:54.010
all your sympathy and respect.

00:49:54.010 --> 00:49:57.030
In how many films does this
guy get blown away at the end.

00:49:57.030 --> 00:50:00.050
But it's a mark
of how subversive,

00:50:00.050 --> 00:50:14.610
how morally turbulent, and
politically and morally engaged

00:50:14.610 --> 00:50:17.700
movies had become by the
early '70s, that's such an

00:50:17.700 --> 00:50:18.900
was possible.

00:50:18.900 --> 00:50:22.950
So, The Parallax View is another
kind of anti-genre in a way.

00:50:22.950 --> 00:50:27.050
It's like a spy film--
in some ways it's

00:50:27.050 --> 00:50:29.930
like one of those Hitchcock
romantic thrillers, in which

00:50:29.930 --> 00:50:33.120
Cary Grant and a
beautiful woman travel

00:50:33.120 --> 00:50:35.760
through beautiful locales and
finally, even though they look

00:50:35.760 --> 00:50:37.780
as if they're in great
danger, win the day

00:50:37.780 --> 00:50:43.010
and are able to marry at the
end then also incidentally,

00:50:43.010 --> 00:50:45.720
have saved the United
States government.

00:50:45.720 --> 00:50:48.720
The film fits that
kind of category,

00:50:48.720 --> 00:50:51.360
but it explodes all
of our expectations

00:50:51.360 --> 00:50:57.970
about the characters and about
the atmosphere of such films.

00:50:57.970 --> 00:50:59.780
And in that sense,
The Parallax View,

00:50:59.780 --> 00:51:05.720
like McCabe &amp; Mrs. Miller,
like Altman's film MASH,

00:51:05.720 --> 00:51:08.800
like his film Nashville,
like the films

00:51:08.800 --> 00:51:12.180
of Martin Scorsese that appear--
Mean Streets, his first film

00:51:12.180 --> 00:51:14.700
and maybe his greatest
film appears in this period

00:51:14.700 --> 00:51:18.890
as well-- have given you a much
grungier, more disturbed, more

00:51:18.890 --> 00:51:24.280
damaged, more hopeless view of
urban violence than any film

00:51:24.280 --> 00:51:25.340
before it had done.

00:51:25.340 --> 00:51:28.680
Again, mobilizing the
genres of the gangster

00:51:28.680 --> 00:51:30.510
film and the urban crime film.

00:51:30.510 --> 00:51:33.460
But mobilizing it in a way that
leaves the viewer unsettled

00:51:33.460 --> 00:51:34.610
and disturbed.

00:51:34.610 --> 00:51:37.780
So the '70s is an
astonishing, remarkable moment

00:51:37.780 --> 00:51:39.300
in the history of American film.

00:51:39.300 --> 00:51:41.320
It's remarkable, not
only because films

00:51:41.320 --> 00:51:43.880
became more courageous
and more dangerous

00:51:43.880 --> 00:51:48.820
in the thematic and moral
sense, but also because it

00:51:48.820 --> 00:51:51.890
was an era in which that
happened in consequence

00:51:51.890 --> 00:51:54.890
of the fact that the
movies had surrendered

00:51:54.890 --> 00:51:57.340
their central place
in American society

00:51:57.340 --> 00:52:00.159
to this new medium
of television.

00:52:00.159 --> 00:52:01.700
I'll talk about some
of these matters

00:52:01.700 --> 00:52:04.700
tonight in a much more
concrete way by looking closely

00:52:04.700 --> 00:52:06.360
at McCabe &amp; Mrs. Miller.

